Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Farid, Mohammad, Hisham, Ali, Hani, Mohamad, Samir, Abbas, Abdullah, Abid, Ahmad, Ahmed.","Muslim: from a personal name based on Arabic <i>farīd</i> ‘unique, matchless’. Compare   Fareed  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fareed","meanings":["Muslim: variant of   Farid  ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Long, Minh, Muoi, Phan, Phat, Vinh, Cuong, Hien, Hoa, Lam, Lan.  Chinese Wing, Chi, Kin, Cheuk, Chi Wai, Chuen, Hon, Keung, Wah, Wai, Chiu, Ho.","Chinese: alternative Mandarin form of the surname 敖, see   Ao  .","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Auerbach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Moshe, Emanuel, Isidor, Bronia, Chaim, Faigy, Menachem, Meyer, Yechezkel.","German: habitational name from any of several places in southern Germany and Austria called Auerbach ‘the stream at the water meadow’. See also 2,   Au  , and   Bach  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from the town of Auerbach in the Upper Palatinate, Bavaria. Compare   Averbach  ."]},{"name":"Ao","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 敖, meaning both ‘rambling’ and ‘deposed king without posthumous titles’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the personal name of <i>Tai Ao</i> (太敖), teacher of the legendary king Zhuanxu (traditional dates: 2514–2437  BC ). (ii) it is said that the surname is also borne by descendants of deposed kings of the former state of Chu, with no posthumous titles, during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Auer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Matthias, Siegfried, Bernd, Bernhard, Erna, Franz, Fritz, Hermann, Horst.","German (mainly Bavaria): topographic name for someone living by a water meadow, German <i>Au</i>, 